 This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Iorwerth ap Cynwrig was born in Tremeirchion, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Cynwrig ap Gruffudd Fychan and Efa verch Llywelyn. He had at least 1 son with Gwladys verch Howel Goeg."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1351–1459":"1351–1459","–Male":"Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1317–1346":"1317–1346","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1459":"1459","1346":"1346","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","Wales":"Wales","of Maenefa,Tremeirchion,Flintshire,Wales":"Tremeirchion, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1351–1459":"1351–1459","–Male":"Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1317–1346":"1317–1346","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1459":"1459","1346":"1346","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","Wales":"Wales","of Maenefa,Tremeirchion,Flintshire,Wales":"Tremeirchion, Flintshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","1351–1459":"1351–1459","–Male":"Décédé","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1317–1346":"1317–1346","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1330–Female":"1330–Décédée","1459":"1459","1346":"1346","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","Wales":"Galles","of Maenefa,Tremeirchion,Flintshire,Wales":"Tremeirchion, Flintshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Iorwerth ap Cynwrig est né à Tremeirchion, Flintshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fils de Cynwrig ap Gruffudd Fychan et Efa verch Llywelyn. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec